<HEADLINE>
<P>
SNOWSTORM SNARLS AIRLINE TRAVEL, CAUSES OUTAGES IN CENTRAL PLAINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Blowing snow snarled airline schedules Wednesday as the latest in a series of 
winter storms whistled from the central Plains into New England, causing power 
outages and traffic accidents. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you're not canceled you're going to be delayed.It's not pleasant," said 
Chicago aviation department spokeswoman Lisa Howard. 
</P>
<P>
 The Federal Aviation Administration ordered airlines to cut arrivals and 
departures at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport by two-thirds because of 
blowing snow and poor visibility. 
</P>
<P>
 New York City's airports reported scattered delays. 
</P>
<P>
 The storm that already had dumped more than a foot of snow on Nebraska brought 
up to 15 inches Wednesday to southern Wisconsin and 11 inches to northern 
Illinois. In the Northeast, up to a foot of snow was forecast in Connecticut 
and Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
 Snow and ice downed power lines in central Illinois, and nearly the entire 
city of Springfield lost electricity during the night. 
</P>
<P>
 In Nebraska, three tractor-trailer rigs and numerous cars were involved in an 
accident that blocked traffic on Interstate 80 between Omaha and Lincoln. 
</P>
