<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL JOURNAL: JUDGE RULES IN FAVOR OF AUDITOR CANDIDATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EMILY ADAMS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Auditor candidate Willy Molnar has survived a legal effort to remove his 
name from the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 A Superior Court judge has ruled that Molnar is qualified for the 
position.Former City Auditor Robert Fronke, who supports the only other auditor 
candidate, incumbent Gary L. Burroughs, had sued to keep Molnar's name off the 
ballot last month, alleging that Molnar failed to meet a city requirement that 
the auditor be licensed as a certified public accountant for five years. 
</P>
<P>
 Molnar received his CPA certificate in 1987 in Michigan, but moved to 
California two years later and did not become licensed in this state until late 
last year. Judge Diane Wayne ruled that Molnar became a CPA more than five 
years ago.  
</P>
<P>
 "It (the court hearing) was over in five minutes," Molnar said. "I feel 
totally vindicated." 
</P>
<P>
 Fronke said he still doesn't believe Molnar has the required experience. 
"Somebody could get a certificate and go work on a farm -- that's not CPA 
experience," he said. EMILY ADAMS 
</P>
