<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Rick VanderKnyf; Eric Bailey, ; Dean Takahashi 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BUZZ: Former astronaut Buzz Aldrin of Laguna Beach heads back into space 
tonight on "The Simpsons." In this episode, NASA chooses Homer to be the first 
average American in space, and Aldrin accompanies him. . . . The popular TV 
cartoon show is "not in my regular repertoire," admits Aldrin, whose voice and 
cartoon image are featured. He is now writing a science-fiction book about 
space travel. "Who knows?" he says. "The aliens could look like the Simpsons, 
though more advanced." 
</P>
<P>
 PLAY NO MORE: Ingram Micro Inc., the worldwide computer distributor in Santa 
Ana, has a policy of not carrying any adult software. Uh, unless by accident. . 
. . PC Week magazine recently discovered that Ingram was distributing copies of 
Playboy's electronic date book last year -- including risque photos of women. A 
spokeswoman told PC Week it had no idea "just how adult" the material was. The 
company says it withdrew the products from distribution once the error was 
discovered. 
</P>
<P>
 MARATHON MAN: The Festival of Whales opens Friday in Dana Point (OC Live!), 
and as might be expected, Laguna Beach-based marine life painter Wyland will be 
part of the action. He'll be honored at a reception Sunday at the Dana Point 
Resort. . . . Wyland, known for painting life-size whale murals around the 
world, plans a whale-painting marathon to begin in August: eight murals in 
eight West Coast cities in eight weeks. . . . His goal is 100 "Whaling Walls" 
by the year 2011. 
</P>
<P>
 HIGH MARKS: Orange County's own state Sen. Marian Bergeson and Assemblyman Tom 
Umberg scored big in California Journal's recent biennial survey ranking state 
legislators. . . . Newport Beach's Bergeson was ranked fourth overall in the 
Senate, and was the highest-scoring Republican in the survey of legislators, 
their staffs, lobbyists and journalists. Umberg, a Garden Grove Democrat 
running for state attorney general, finished 10th in the 80-member Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
