COMMUNITY NEWS; AVALON; RECREATION PROGRAM PLANNED FOR YOUTHS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A recreation program designed to help keep Catalina Island teen-agers out of 
trouble is being planned for Avalon's Tremont Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 The Santa Catalina Company recently offered to let the city of Avalon use the 
building at no charge. 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council has applied for a $40,000 grant from the Los Angeles County 
Regional Park District to renovate the hall and establish the program for 
at-risk youths. 
</P>
<P>
 Because there are few recreational activities in Avalon, nearly all of the 
island's 700 youths are "at risk," said Anni Marshall, community services 
director. 
</P>
<P>
 Teen-agers "will get into drugs and alcohol because there's not much to do," 
said Councilwoman Barbara J. Doutt. 
</P>
<P>
 The program will offer such classes as self-defense, ballet and acting. SUSAN 
WOODWARD 
</P>
