348 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEIGHBORHOOD EATERY: SOUTH BAY GETS A TASTE OF MOROCCO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The diverse Lawndale dining scene, with restaurants featuring the foods of 
Persia, Cuba, Peru, Thailand and Vietnam as well as the more familiar Italian, 
Chinese, Japanese and Mexican establishments, has an exotic new addition -- the 
month-old Dar Salam, which offers the cuisine of Morocco.  
</P>
<P>
 Dar Salam, Arabic for "house of peace," is owned by Hassan Elfarissi, who 
immigrated to America in 1983 from Casablanca, Morocco. When his sister, Soud, 
arrived recently, they decided to open a restaurant. Like so many other 
restaurant owners, they have no formal training, but were blessed with having 
been raised by a mother who was a good cook. 
</P>
<P>
 At lunch, a popular choice is couscous with beef sirloin and a variety of 
vegetables ($6.75). For this dish, couscous, a grain-shaped steamed pasta that 
is a staple throughout North Africa, is mixed with raisins and onions. Another 
option is a brochette of beef ($6), served on a mound of rice. Another dish 
consists of a large plate of rice ($4.50) served with tuna, scrambled eggs and 
olives.  
</P>
<P>
 Most dinners begin with harira , a tomato-based vegetable soup garnished with 
oil-cured olives. The soup is usually followed with bestila , a sort of pie 
where phyllo dough encases layers of ground almonds, shredded chicken and eggs 
mixed with onions, all flavored with cinnamon, parsley and cilantro. This tasty 
dish is traditionally eaten with one's fingers.  
</P>
<P>
 Three multi-course dinners ($15) are offered, each named for a city in 
Morocco. The Fez features the harira soup, a spicy carrot salad or lentil 
salad, bestila , couscous with raisins and a leg of lamb with dried plums and 
sesame seeds. The Marrakesh is similar but the main course is leg of lamb with 
cinnamon, almonds and eggs. And what would a Moroccan menu be without a mention 
of Casablanca, which highlights a baked chicken with olives and lemons? 
</P>
<P>
 I bet that's what Humphrey Bogart would order. Here's cookin' at you, kid. 
</P>
<P>
 Dar Salam is at 14940 S. Prairie Ave., Lawndale. (310 ) 675-5850. Open seven 
days 11 a.m. to 10 p.m. MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Restaurant Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
