<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; CITY WILL BUY 11 LOTS ON RIDGELINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks will purchase 11 prominent ridgeline lots in the Skyline Area 
for $46,750 after all, as Councilman Frank Schillo has reversed his earlier 
"no" vote and decided to endorse the acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
 A tour of the area persuaded him that the parcels would make an ideal trail 
head for hikers and equestrians, Schillo said. Although last week he voted 
against the purchase, arguing that the city should spend the money elsewhere, 
Schillo said he changed his mind after learning that the Skyline Area lots link 
up to the Los Robles trail system. 
</P>
<P>
 On Tuesday night, he called on his colleagues to rescind last week's vote and 
start the debate afresh. Bolstered by the new information, Councilwoman Jaime 
Zukowski joined Schillo in changing from a "no" to a "yes" vote. 
</P>
<P>
 "My eyes have been opened -- this is a good opportunity for us," Schillo said. 
"I'm convinced that trail heads are pretty important to our community. Here's a 
chance to buy one for $46,000 and at the same time, eliminate the possibility 
that someone will come and build a house on one of those parcels, a house that 
could be seen from as far away as Agoura." 
</P>
<P>
 In the end, Mayor Elois Zeanah cast the only vote opposing purchase of the 
Skyline Area lots, which are on sale because the property owner has failed to 
pay taxes for the past seven years. 
</P>
<P>
 Zeanah said she could not support using park funds, which come from the taxes 
developers pay on each bedroom they build in the community, for the purchase. 
She also chastised Schillo for seeking to change his vote. 
</P>
<P>
 But other council members called the purchase a bargain. They pointed out that 
the city recently approved several goals for the Skyline Area, including 
acquisition of sensitive ridgeline lots to preserve the region's rural feel. 
</P>
<P>
 City Manager Grant Brimhall said Wednesday he believes the sale will go 
through soon. The Ventura County tax collector is obligated to offer the 
property to the city before auctioning it to private developers, he said. 
STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</TEXT>
