<P>
 Treasury Note Yields Rise in Auction: Amid fears of further Federal Reserve 
Board interest rate increases, investors shunned the government's auction of 
new two-year notes Wednesday and, in response, traders sent yields of Treasury 
securities sharply higher.Yields on the two-year notes rose to the highest 
level in 14 months. The high yield was 4.66%, up from 4.11% at the last auction 
Jan. 25. It was the highest rate since two-year notes sold for 4.71% on Dec. 
22, 1992. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 4.625%, with each 
$10,000 in face value selling for $9,993.40. A total of $17 billion in notes 
were sold. 
</P>
