<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; OLYMPICS PUSHES CBS TO HIGHEST-RATED WEEK IN HISTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE MARGULIES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There was the Winter Olympics, and then there was everything else. That's how 
last week's prime-time TV ratings broke down in the figures released Wednesday 
by the A.C. Nielsen Co. "60 Minutes" tied for seventh place with Day 3 of CBS' 
snow-and-ice games, but ABC's "Home Improvement," which followed at No. 9, was 
three points behind--meaning it reached 2.8 million fewer homes than the 
lowest-rated Olympics broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
 CBS said it was the network's highest-rated week in history, and the largest 
audiences ever for Olympics programming--summer or winter. On average, the 
network's prime-time schedule attracted 40% of the available audience last 
week--a whopping 24.4 million homes, compared to9.8 million for ABC, 8.5 
million for NBC and 6.9 million for Fox. 
</P>
<P>
 ABC had been making a run at CBS in recent weeks, but CBS is now assured of 
winning the prime-time season for the third year in a row. 
</P>
<P>
 National A.C. Nielsen Ratings 
</P>
<P>
 Here are the ratings for national prime-time television last week (Feb. 14-22) 
as compiled by the A. C. Nielsen Co. Each rating point is said by Nielsen to 
represent 942,000 homes, or 1% of the 94.2 million U.S. households that have 
TV. Southland Ratings 
</P>
<P>
 Here are A. C. Nielsen's Top 10 prime-time programs in the Los Angeles area 
during the same week. Each rating point equals 50,064 households. 
