<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIRLS' SWIMMING AND DIVING '94 / SIX TEAMS TO WATCH; EL TORO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Coach: Sheri Ross (25th year). 
</P>
<P>
 1993: South Coast League champion; Division I champion. 
</P>
<P>
 Key returners: Kenesha Jespersen, So., diving; Katie Lowes, So.; Katie 
Simmons, So.; Amy Sloan, Jr., diving; A.J. Walters, Sr.; Becky Wilshire, Jr., 
diving. 
</P>
<P>
 Key newcomers: Christie Kennedy, Fr. 
</P>
<P>
 Outlook: The top three places at the Division I championship meet were a clean 
sweep for the talent-heavy South Coast League, and El Toro led every step of 
the way. The Chargers won a school-record eighth league championship and every 
meet -- dual, invitational, postseason -- they entered, including their 
first-ever section championship. This year, the finish could be eerily similar, 
though Ross said depth might be a concern. The most prominent name missing is 
Michelle Perry, winner of three consecutive 100-yard section freestyle titles, 
who now swims for UCLA. As much publicity as Capistrano Valley divers get, El 
Toro has some threats of its own. Sloan, Jespersen and Wilshire finished 
second, eighth and 12th at the section meet, and all are back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
