<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; EGYPT; PROGRESS REPORTED IN ISRAEL-PLO TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Israeli and Palestine Liberation Organization negotiators meeting in Cairo 
reported progress toward implementing their accord on limited Palestinian 
self-rule in the occupied territories. In a joint statement issued at the end 
of three days of talks, negotiators said they still need more time to resolve 
security and administrative issues and hope for further progress when talks 
resume next week.The latest round of talks focused on security arrangements for 
the Gaza Strip and the West Bank town of Jericho, the size of the Palestinian 
police force and where Palestinian police will be deployed. In Jerusalem, 
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said Israeli troops can withdraw from the 
Gaza Strip and the West Bank region of Jericho four weeks after Israel and the 
PLO resolve disputes holding up an autonomy agreement. 
</P>
