<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; HONG KONG; LEGISLATURE OKS INITIAL REFORMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gov. Chris Patten's push for electoral reform in Hong Kong, despite strong 
Chinese government opposition, cleared its first legislative hurdle.The British 
colony's 60-member Legislative Council overwhelmingly passed a "first stage" 
reform bill containing the least controversial elements of a reform package 
that Patten unveiled in October, 1992. The bill's passage allows Patten to 
begin work on a second bill containing further reforms. That bill -- which 
China finds even more objectionable -- includes steps to significantly broaden 
the voting base for future elections. China says it will scrap such reforms 
when it assumes control of the colony in 1997. 
</P>
